== Consistent GTK+ 3 theme ==

=== Native Xfce theme engine ===
Xfce's own theme engine, <code>x11-themes/gtk-engines-xfce</code>, was recently updated to version 3.0, which implements native support for GTK+ 3 with no further configuration.

Assuming that you have <code>gtk3</code> in your USE flags, the GTK+ 3 version (<code>-r300</code>) should be pulled in by default if you have <code>xfce-base/xfce4-meta</code> or <code>x11-themes/gtk-engines-xfce</code> in your world set and you do a world upgrade with the <code>--deep</code> option. If it does not, simply do a:

{{Emerge|x11-themes/gtk-engines-xfce}}

This should pull in a version of <code>x11-themes/gtk-engines-xfce</code> with the suffix <code>-r300</code> in a new slot.

After emerging the GTK+ 3 version of <code>x11-themes/gtk-engines-xfce</code>, applications using GTK+ 3 should now blend nicely with applications using GTK+ 2 when you use one of the native Xfce themes.

=== Greybird theme ===
Another option is to use the [http://shimmerproject.org/project/greybird/ Greybird] theme, which has support for GTK+ 2, GTK+ 3, xfwm4, emerald, & metacity.
{{Emerge|x11-themes/greybird}}

Go to Xfce menu -> Settings -> Appearance. Or run xfce4-appearance-settings.  Select "Greybird" from the "Style" list.

Now GTK+ 2 and GTK+ 3 applications should have consistent look.

